Here's a bug that isn't a bug — and it might be doubling your Spark bill. By default, Spark recomputes an RDD from scratch every time you use it.

Remember lineage: an RDD is just a recipe. So when you call count on it, Spark runs the whole recipe. Then you call collect on the same RDD — and Spark runs the entire recipe again, from the original source. Two actions, twice the work.

The fix is caching. Call cache, and Spark materializes the RDD on the first action and reuses it after that — no recomputation. cache keeps it in memory.

If you need more control, use persist and choose a storage level. MEMORY_ONLY is pure RAM. MEMORY_AND_DISK spills to disk when RAM runs out — that's the default for DataFrames. There's DISK_ONLY, serialized levels that trade CPU for less memory, and replicated levels ending in two.

One habit: call unpersist when you're done. A cache holds onto executor memory until you release it, and that memory isn't free.

Caching is Module 3 — link's in the description.
